🔹 What new Does

When you use new with a function:

Creates a new empty object
Sets the object’s prototype to the constructor’s prototype
Calls the constructor function with this pointing to the new object
Returns the new object (unless constructor explicitly returns another object)

🔹 Constructor Functions
A constructor function is just a regular function intended to create objects.
By convention, its name starts with a capital letter.
 

function Person(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
    this.greet = function() {
        console.log(`Hello, I am ${this.name}`);
    };
}

const person1 = new Person("Rahul", 25);
const person2 = new Person("Neha", 30);

person1.greet(); // Hello, I am Rahul
person2.greet(); // Hello, I am Neha



🔹 Step-by-Step Object Creation with new
1. new Person("Rahul", 25)
2. Creates empty object {}
3. Links __proto__ to Person.prototype
4. Calls Person() with this = new object
5. Properties and methods added to this
6. Returns the object

🔹 Prototype Linking
Every function in JS has a prototype property
Objects created with new link their __proto__ to this prototype

console.log(person1.__proto__ === Person.prototype); // true


| Concept     | Example              |
| ----------- | -------------------- |
| Constructor | `Person` function    |
| Instance    | `person1`, `person2` |
| Prototype   | `Person.prototype`   |

🔹 Prototype Sharing

Person.prototype.sayBye = function() {
    console.log(`${this.name} says bye`);
};

person1.sayBye(); // Rahul says bye
person2.sayBye(); // Neha says bye

Shared method is not duplicated in each instance
Saves memory and keeps code DRY

Person() function
